Title: The Pragmatic Programmer: From Journeyman to Master
Author: Andy Hunt

Title: All About Love: New Visions
Author: bell hooks
My Review:
i used to tell people that we don’t tell the people we love that we love them enough. after reading this book, i want to add that the world is filled with so much love, but we just don’t know how to express it.

as commonly stated in the book, love is as love does. in life, if there’s one thing to carry, it’s to love deeply and love genuinely, both for others and for yourself. <3

Title: Sense and Sensibility
Author: Jane Austen
Additional Authors: Джейн Остин, Ros Ballaster, Mobile Classics, Силвия Желева
My Review: wow. beyond lucky that this was my first jane austen novel. the portrayal of sisterhood, and their respective experiences of unrequited love, was iconic. loved that while they seemed to be complete opposites of each other in the beginning, they both hold parts of their sister, and that showed more as i continued to read. so much drama and emotion, i was in a constant state of awe. couldn’t shut up about it and will never shut up about it.

Title: The White Castle
Author: Orhan Pamuk
My Review:
ngl, while reading, at times i thought the book was slow.
but after finishing it, i really loved it.
love how hoja and the italian slave go into why we are the way we are, whether or not our mistakes define us, what role our childhood experiences play into who we are and how we influence each other/to what extent to we influence each other.
the last chapter was confusing in that you question who the narrator was and who “He” is.
if anything, love the book, but i def need to reread it with an older perspective.

Title: Writers & Lovers
Author: Lily King
My Review: honestly, it was a rollercoaster. in the end, it had me crying. team silas all the way. but really, i loved casey and i loved being able to find parts of myself in her. like i’ve said before, i love how the universe works in a way that the books i read line up almost perfectly to what i’m going through in my life.

My Review:
must read especially in your early 20s!!!!!!!
a good book that makes you question what you think you know about your life and then you realize that you kinda know a little bit, and you really don’t know a lot. and that’s okay, if not better, as we keep going :)

Title: The Witch of Portobello
Author: Paulo Coelho
My Review:
things i’ve learned from reading this book:
1. i’d rather do things in the unconventional way and be happy than follow society and be bored.
2. take the risk and do the hard stuff. if you fail, just enjoy it and move on - you learned something.
3. love simply is.
